    value: 도박하는 자가 돈댄 것이 다 되면, 있는대로 털어 내 놓는데 이것을 고주(孤注)라 한다. 《宋史 寇準傳》
english:
  title: A Preface to Appreciating the Plum Blossoms at the Residence of the Leader of the Royal Secretariat
  author: Kim Su-on
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Flowers have long held a special place in human affection, yet none more so than the plum blossom. Poets compose verses in its praise, nobles cultivate it in their gardens, and even recluses, hermit scholars, and followers of Buddha and Tao place it in earthenware vessels and tend it with devotion. All treasure the plum above all else, lavishing upon it such care and affection that they seem willing to die for it. What charm does the plum possess to inspire such extraordinary devotion?

    Consider the progression through the lunar calendar: from the first month of yin through the second month of yin, extending to the sixth month of yin. According to the symbolism of the Changes, all yang has been consumed and stripped away. The superior returns to the inferior—this is the hexagram of Return, corresponding to the eleventh lunar month. Heaven and earth close; grasses and trees wither. The ruler suspends his travels; merchants cease their journeys. As the poet Liu Zongyuan wrote: "From ten thousand peaks, all birds have vanished; along countless paths, human traces are erased." Such is the desolation of winter's grip.

    Yet at this very moment, when yin reaches its zenith, the plum blossoms forth with radiance. Through the mist and murk, life's abundance unfolds. At the culmination of darkness emerges the warmth of light. The sage who studies the Changes perceives in this the very heart of heaven and earth, and marvels at it ceaselessly.

    I had long heard of the magnificent plum blossoms at the residence of the Leader, and upon visiting, I found one tree in full bloom while another had already withered and yellowed. I jested with my host: "The flowers open, eager to flourish, yet scatter and nearly vanish. The visitor comes early, yet the host does not invite him. Is this the flower's misfortune, or the guest's? Can you make the plum blossom before winter's end, or cause it to bloom after spring has come, surpassing all other flowers?"

    The host replied: "Not so. By exposing it to daylight and sheltering it at night, covering it and pouring warm water upon it, the warmth lingers while the cold cannot penetrate. Thus it blooms before spring. This is the method of yang subduing yin. Should one prevent blooming and cause it to bloom when it should not, this requires yin to restrain yang—a principle contrary to the Changes' elevation of yang, and thus contrary to the Way of Heaven and Earth."

    I answered: "Then is not what you accomplish an ordering of the pre-celestial, while what you cannot accomplish belongs to the post-celestial? Yet consider: heaven and earth close themselves so thoroughly, grasses and trees wither so completely, and still the plum blooms thus. How can your exposure to daylight and the light from eaves' gaps be sufficient to reverse the transformations of creation and produce blossoms in the depth of winter?"

    The host said: "Nevertheless, it is still the power of yin and yang and creation's work."

    I replied: "Not at all. It is neither yin nor yang, neither creation's work, nor human artifice. The plum blooms of itself. How do I know the plum blooms of itself? Does not the Changes say: 'All things each contain one Great Ultimate'? If one thing contains one Great Ultimate, then when it divides into yin and yang, cold and heat, blooming and fading, does not each follow its own nature freely?"

    With that, we both laughed heartily. Shortly after, the Duke of Yicheng, the Duke of Seopyeong, and the Duke of Jinsan arrived in succession. Resplendent in literary and moral accomplishment, dignified in rank and station, they took their seats in order, appearing like immortals. The host brought forth fine wine and rare delicacies, pouring from ancient bronze vessels of the Yin dynasty, displaying ritual bronzes of the Zhou. The fragrant sweetness of ancient libations mingled with the warming vapors of rare mountain wines. When the rituals concluded, host and guests shared in joyful revelry.

    The Duke of Yicheng first composed a verse: "When a renowned flower meets a renowned minister, the two together appear." I responded: "On this day, at this hour, how precious the sight." Others contributed their own compositions, omitting or adding phrases as they saw fit. The tones rose and fell in succession; jade pendants rang in harmony. All the transformations of heaven, earth, yin, yang, and creation—the movements of wind and cloud, moon and dew, birds and beasts—were encompassed within our verses, yet all centered upon a single subject: the plum blossom.

    This is because today the plum is our sole concern. Once the sage Shao Yong, studying the Changes, found in the plum the principles of cosmic transformation and developed a numerical system called "Observing the Plum." Scholars said he captured the numbers but missed the principles, and few wished to study it. Yet by the standard of the plum itself, it was a great fortune for the flower. Now you, living after Shao Yong's time, emulate his learning. The plum remains the plum; the numbers remain the numbers. What you have illuminated in the plum reaches to all depths. Thus the numbers arising from the plum transcend nothing—one could say this is the plum's second great fortune. Believing me deeply versed in the principles of the Changes, you have asked me to set brush to paper and compose this preface to the plum blossoms.
